I'm both professionally and academically very acquainted with "food" and have a disease which forced me to study this shit like nothing else

Here are things you should be eating:

1. Liver (once every few days), this one's obvious
2. Cow/pig/lamb/chicken hearts - massive cq10 source as well as the usual shtick
3. Braising meats (such as beef short ribs/chuck roasts) - you want to consume the collagen in the meat, now turned gelatin, which provides you with fantastic flavour and additional easily digestible protein, as well as helping your GI tract heal from irritation/inflammation. Make sure to drink the braising liquid or reuse for another dish. Can also be done with a slowcooker.
4. Ginger (either fresh slices for your tea or cooking)
5. Lemons/Limes - do not underestimate the role of vitamin C is collagen synthesis
6. Kiwi - one of the most nutrition fruits per pound there is, and vitamin K source
7. Banana - banana :)
8. Blueberries
9. Spices (not spicy) - look up the micros in things like cumin/cinnamon/turmeric/etc, the east knows what they're doing. Explore middle eastern/indian cuisine while you're at it.
10. Fermented produce
11. Eggs

Things you PROBABLY should be eating

1.Sweet potatoes
2. Beetroot
3. Apple cider vinegar (a teaspoon to start with after food)
4. Macadamia nuts - monosaturated fat as opposed to PUFAs compared to other nuts
5. Brazil nuts (don't go over a few a day)
6. Cheese/milk/yoghurt - whatever you can very confidently handle, ruining your GI lining is not worth it
7. Carrots

Things you probably shouldn't be eating, or at least not regularly

1. Grains
2. Alcohol
3. Most nuts/seeds
4. Oxalate sources

>>69346246
yeah you're definitely setting up a little loose, hips too low, and not locking out aggressively enough. After you grab the bar, lock in your lats. It should feel like you're forcing your shoulders down, not back, but also not forward. I'm also not seeing an obvious brace. From newbies especially I want to see a cartoonish, open mouth deep breath before the pull. Ideally you'd do like 1k does where you take that breath before taking your grip but that requires a better muscle memory for your setup than you have yet. Instead, once you get the bar and your feet set and you know where your hips need to be at the pull, keep your hands on the bar but do whatever you need to do to make room for a big breath. /smg/ raises his hips to do that for example. Then you want to bring all that muscle and air tension and wedge it between the bar and the floor by driving the hips in. I think you can definitely get 3pl8 by January based on that bar speed.

Because the weight is "dead". In most olympic lifts you are allowed (and encouraged) to use the stretch effect of the muscle to provide a "boost". This is especially true with a proper depth squat. Your tightened quads will provide some instantaneous energy coming out of the box, allowing you to lift more. In a deadlift the weight is static the entire way through the lift. There's no opportunity to utilize the stretch of the muscle to power through.

posts.name: Anonymous

>>69348099
The strictest definition is that lean mass is body weight less fat. We can think of it as body weight multiplied by one minus your body fat percentage.

For example, if you plan to be 120 kg at 20% BF, your lean mass will be 96 kg, so you'll want to eat ~100 g of protein per day.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>69329705
Your neurons use a variety of ions, Na, Ca, K, etc. to work properly. You already get plenty of NaCl from food. So you want a mix of other salts.
And type of salt matters. MgSO4 is used by pretty much all the cheaper mixes, but it dissolves poorly in water, isn't absorbed as well as other forms, therefore they add more of it, and you get insolvable sediment in your bottle. That, and in large amounts it's a laxative. Same with other elements, their salt forms have different properties.

Additionally, sea salt has salts other than NaCl, so it could be used to get more necessary ions with food, but pretty much all sea salt has microplastics nowadays as well.

>Advice for new runners

>>69336439
1. The further north of the equator you go, the less UVA and UVB radiation actually makes it to the surface any time of the year due to the angle of the atmosphere relative to the sun. This makes you need much longer time in the sun to get the same effects, which is even worse in the winter where the angle weakens the sun's radiation even further.

2. You need 15-20 minutes of direct southern summer sun with 20-25% of your skin exposed to it, which is not so easy when it's 10-20F outside all day on a "warm" day and you need to cover up to avoid frostbite. In the winter in the north you might need 2-3 times that amount of time (due to point 1) which means staying outside for up to an hour with no shirt on in below freezing or potentially even below-zero weather.

3. The sky is overcast almost always in the winter so it's rare to actually even get direct sunlight that isn't filtered through clouds in the first place. I go outside multiple times per day and I haven't seen direct sunlight in over a week.

It's not as simple as "just go outside for a bit." Even if us northerners DO go outside in the winter we're not getting any direct sunlight and only a very small amount of our skin (face and MAYBE hands) is exposed to this very weak and overcast sun. Even with super pale complexion it's not enough and supplementation is necessary to maintain healthy vitamin D levels.

>>69347771
Full body all workout days.
At the gym do heavy compounds and specialty isolation work like leg press, leg extensions, cable work etc.
At home either a full body dumbbell circuit or, a full body workout.

Aim for 3-4 training days. 2 in gym, 1-2 dB work at home.

Example of a full body dB routine:
Lower body: Choose any 3
DB squats 4 x 8-12
DB Bulgarian split squats 4 x 8-12
DB lunges 4 x 12-15
DB RDL 4 x 12-15
DB Single Leg DL 4 x 8-12 (each leg)

Chest: Choose any 3
DB floor press 4 x 12-15
DB incline press 4 x 8-12
DB fly 4 x 12-15
DB front raise (supine grip) 4 x 8-12

Back: Choose any 3
DB reverse fly 4 x 12-15
DB bent over rows 4 x 12-15 (supinated or pronated grip position)
Single arm DB row 4 x 12-15

Pull ups 4 X AMRAP

>>69323811
I've grown up my whole life disabled anon. I won't specify further, because it's rare enough that the exact disability is basically doxing myself. I got really lucky, I can walk, I can lift things (though nothing too heavy) and I can get up from the floor (albeit with access to a wall or something to pull myself up).
As a result of my disability while growing up I spent a lot of time in various medical facilities and met other children with other disabilities. These ranged from kids with progressing degenerative muscle deseases, over mental impairments to your average wheelchair bound kid. Some had diseases that progressed, some didn't. Those who had diseases that progressed usually had a few years left to live, though those last 2 years I'd hardly call "living", it's essentially waiting in a hospital bed until your lungs or heart give out.
You know what all those kids had in common?
I never met one who was bitter about their situation. They were sad, or frustrated at times, but never bitter. They all had dreams and aspirations as any other kid would.
One wheelchair bound kid I was friends with for a few weeks in a facility could barely stand outside his wheelchair, but to him the important part was that he could somewhat stand, sometimes even take a few steps. So, for the short time I knew him, he tried every day. A good third of the times he'd collapse, pull himself up into the wheelchair on his arms and try again.
These kids taught me a lot, and while I was blessed to be able to live a relatively normal life (as in I don't need a caretaker), I never quite forgot them when I am lazy or can't get the motivation to do sports.

Because how could I in good concience waste a gift that I have that these kids dream their entire life of experiencing?
How could I look into their eyes and tell the kid who fights daily just to be able to stand that I, who can walk up stairs, can't be bothered to exercise today because I am lazy?
I couldn't. And so I don't.
